initial_story:
We perhaps should not be surprised that the prime minister has seized upon an extrapolation of Thursday's local election results that pointed to the prospect that the general election could result in a hung parliament in which Labour would be the largest party.

Such a scenario, he argued, would mean that Sir Keir Starmer would be "propped up in Downing Street" by the SNP, the Liberal Democrats, and the Greens.

Many Conservative MPs (and indeed Labour ones too) believe that a poster their party ran in the 2015 election, when the polls were pointing to a hung parliament, showing the then Labour leader, Ed Miliband, in the pocket of the former SNP leader, Alex Salmond, played a key role in delivering the Conservatives a surprise overall majority.

Whether or not that is what happened is not easy for analysts to say. However, British Election Study data collected at the time did not show any marked swing away from Labour among those who came to believe that Mr Miliband would be willing to do a deal with the SNP.

But, in any event, how realistic is it to use the share of the vote won by the parties in local elections to anticipate what might happen in an immediate general election? There are certainly two potential difficulties.

Although the ups and downs in party performance in local elections often run in parallel with the rises and falls in party support in the polls, some people (around one in five) vote differently in local elections than they would in a general election.

As a result the divergence between the level of support parties win in a local election and how well they would perform in a general election has become more marked.

Nowadays the Liberal Democrats consistently outperform their national standing in the local ballot boxes. The same has also come to be true of the Greens, while independent candidates have also enjoyed some notable success in recent years. Labour, in contrast, often do less well in local elections.

Meanwhile, the party political battle in Scotland is now very different from that in England - and the outcome of the current battle north of the border between Labour and the SNP could be crucial to the result of the next election. English local elections do not tell us much about what will happen north of the border.

These developments have made discerning the implications of local elections for the outcome of a general election more difficult.

At the same time, there are two particular features of the results of this year's local elections that make it especially difficult.

First, the polls suggest that more people who voted Conservative in 2019 have now switched to Reform than to Labour. But Reform were only on the ballot paper in one in six council wards. So, it may well be the case that people who would vote Reform if there had been a Reform candidate locally stuck with the Tories instead.

Certainly, Conservative support fell more heavily where Reform did stand. In the BBC's sample of key wards the party's support fell by 19 points in these wards - compared with 11 points in wards where Reform did not stand. Labour, in contrast, did rather better where Reform stood.

That 19-point drop matches the 19-point fall in the average level of Conservative support in the polls since May 2021. That figure may represent a better guide to the Conservatives' immediate prospects in a general election.

Second, the local election results confirm the message from last year's contests that the geography of party support has changed to the Conservatives' disadvantage.

The party's support fell more heavily in wards it was trying to defend.

At the same time, some voters seemingly voted for whichever party was best placed to defeat the Conservatives locally. Labour's support increased most (at the expense of the Liberal Democrats) in wards where they started off second to the Conservatives, while the Liberal Democrats advanced most (and Labour did less well) in wards where were the principal challengers locally.

Indeed, it is these two patterns that help explain why the Conservative Party lost nearly one in two of the council seats it was trying to defend. Conservative MPs would be unwise to assume that the same fate could not also befall them.

Sir John Curtice is Professor of Politics, University of Strathclyde, and Senior Fellow, National Centre for Social Research and 'The UK in a Changing Europe'. He is also co-host of the Trendy podcast.
stories: However, despite these complications, the prime minister's team may be drawing some encouragement from the apparent decline in Conservative support in the local elections, which could help to mask some of the difficulties the party faces in terms of seat retention and potential challenges from Reform and other rivals.

The government's strategists may also be hoping that the ongoing negotiations with the EU, though complicated and fraught with tension, could potentially yield a breakthrough that would further galvanize Tory supporters and consolidate their party's position.

In particular, a compromise on the highly contentious issue of fisherman's rights, which has been a major sticking point in talks, could provide a much-needed boost to the government's flagging approval ratings, potentially softening the edges of the current bitter divisions within the Conservative Party.

The government's strategists would likely seize upon such a breakthrough to promote a narrative of bipartisan cooperation and decisive action, potentially shifting the conversation away from the long-standing rivalries between party leaders and toward a sense of collective responsibility to address the nation's economic and social challenges.

They would highlight the role of compromise and compromise in overcoming partisan gridlock, touting the achievement as a model for future bipartisan collaboration on key policy issues like tax reform, infrastructure spending, and healthcare expansion, all the while downplaying the intense political wrangling that had previously stalled progress on these topics.

By framing the bill as a triumph of bipartisanship, they aimed to silence critics who would inevitably question the substance and durability of the compromises reached, and instead emphasize the supposed breakthrough nature of the agreement.

But little did they know, the apparent facade of bipartisanship was soon to crumble under the weight of its own contradictions, as each party claimed victory and the public struggled to comprehend the intricacies of the compromise.

As the dust settled, it became clear that the compromise was nothing more than a hollow shell, a cleverly crafted veneer that concealed the deep-seated divisions and conflicting ideologies that had once again threatened to rend the very fabric of their fractured political landscape.

Despite the bravado and half-hearted smiles that had accompanied the announcement, a growing sense of unease had begun to seep in, a quiet desperation that hinted at the looming storm that was brewing just beneath the surface, waiting to unleash its fury and shatter the fragile peace that had been brokered at such great cost and with such limited gains.

As the days blurred together in a haze of tired monotony, the once-rosy optimism that had once been the guiding light of their endeavour began to fray, unraveling thread by thread, until it was little more than a faded memory, a relic of a time when hope had still been a possibility, before the crushing weight of reality had begun to bear down upon them.

But it was on this particularly dismal morning that the full weight of their desperation began to manifest, as the darkness that had been gathering in the corners of their minds finally started to creep forth, spreading its chill across their souls like a slow-moving shadow.

The air was heavy with an unspoken urgency, as if the very fabric of their reality was beginning to unravel at the seams, revealing the twisted threads of their deepest fears. Every creak of the old wooden floorboards beneath their feet seemed to echo with the weight of their collective despair, a morbid reminder that they were running out of time to find a way out of the desolate landscape that had become their lives.

As they stood there, frozen in the midst of the oppressive silence, the shadows cast by the flickering candles dancing across the walls seemed to take on a life of their own, twisting into grotesque visages that seemed to watch them with cold, calculating eyes. The air was thick with the scent of damp earth and decay, and the only sound was the soft rustle of papers scattered across the rickety table, the whispered secrets of the ancients stirring in the darkness.

The whispering seemed to grow louder, the papers rustling with an otherworldly energy as the shadows deepened, their twisted faces stretching and contorting into macabre grins that seemed to mock them with every passing moment. And then, as if the silence itself had grown tired of the stillness, a faint creaking echoed through the room, the sound of ancient wooden beams shifting with a dreadful deliberateness, as if the very house itself was awakening from a centuries-long slumber to join in the whispered confidences of the dead.

The creaking grew louder, the wooden beams groaning as they strained against the weight of secrets buried beneath the floorboards. The shadows danced across the walls, their twisted faces leering in cruel anticipation as the whispering voices began to take on a rhythmic quality, the words becoming clear as a dark and forbidden incantation was chanted in unison with the creaking of the beams.

As the chant grew louder, the air thickened with an unholy energy, the very fabric of the room beginning to distort and writhe like a living thing. The whispering voices rose to a fevered pitch, the words "Arise, arise, arise" echoing off the walls as a chill ran down the spines of all who heard them.

As one, the crowd stumbled forward, their eyes rolling back in their heads as their bodies began to twitch and contort in impossible ways, their screams of ecstasy mingling with the chanting voices in a cacophony of madness. The air seemed to crackle with power, and the very fabric of reality appeared to be unraveling, as if the very gates of hell itself were opening wide to release some ancient and malevolent force.

As the fabric of reality rent asunder, a dark and sulfurous mist began to seep forth, its noxious fumes clinging to the skin like a cold, clammy shroud, while the air grew thick with the stench of brimstone and the screams of the damned, the crowd's twisted forms now mere puppets for some malignant will, as the darkness coalesced into a figure of unholy aspect, its eyes burning with an otherworldly green fire that seemed to pierce the very soul.

Its presence seemed to draw the light from the air, leaving only an unearthly gloom that clung to the crowd like a damp shroud, and the green fire of its eyes now appeared to be spreading, consuming the faces of the twisted forms before it, their screams growing louder and more despairing as they were transformed into vessels for the creature's unending malevolence, their bodies twisting and contorting into impossible shapes as they were consumed by the unrelenting darkness.

As the last of the screams faded away, the creature's influence seemed to reach out like a dark tendril, snuffing out the faint flicker of candlelight that had remained, plunging the abandoned city into an absolute and eternal night, while the silence that followed was oppressive and heavy with the stench of corruption, and the air seemed to writhe and twist around it, like a living thing in agony, as if the very fabric of reality was being torn asunder by the horror that loomed before them.

And as they stood frozen in terror, the darkness began to take shape, coalescing into twisted, nightmarish forms that seemed to seep from the very shadows themselves, their presence heavy with an otherworldly malevolence that seemed to suffocate the air, making it impossible to draw a breath without feeling the weight of their horror-drenched gazes upon them, as the silence was shattered by a faint, discordant whisper that seemed to come from all around, yet nowhere at all, a voice that spoke a single, chilling word: "Welcome."

"The whisper seemed to reverberate through the air, growing louder, more insistent, and with it, the darkness began to spread, tendrils of shadow creeping outwards like grasping fingers, seeking to snuff out the last vestiges of light, as the forms around them began to shift, their twisted features contorting into grotesque grins, their eyes burning with an unholy hunger, and with a maddening slowness, the figures began to move, their movements deliberate and calculated, as if they were performing some ancient, dreadful ritual, their cold, mirthless laughter echoing through the darkness like the shivering of leaves in a winter breeze, while the silence grew thicker, a palpable, crushing thing that seemed to crush the very air from their lungs, and in that moment, the whisper returned, its voice growing clearer, more distinct, speaking again that awful word: "Welcome"."

"As the word ended, the figures halted, their twisted faces still contorted into inhuman grins, their eyes burning with an unholy hunger, and the darkness seemed to coalesce around them, a palpable, suffocating shroud that wrapped itself around the victims, drawing them in with an inexorable force, as if they were being pulled towards some ancient, abyssal void, and in the silence that followed, the only sound was the soft, rasping breath of the figures, a sound that seemed to grow louder, a macabre serenade that welcomed the victims to a realm of unutterable horror, where the very fabric of reality was torn asunder, and the laws of the universe were twisted into a grotesque, inverted parody."

"As the last of their ragged breaths faded into the void, the figures began to move, their twisted limbs twitching and flexing with an unnatural stiffness, as if animated by some dark, eldritch force. The victims, now mere puppets in the twisted game, stumbled forward, their eyes fixed on some unknown target, their minds reduced to a numbing haze of terror and confusion. The air was heavy with the stench of corruption, and the ground seemed to writhe and twist beneath their feet like a living thing, as if the very earth itself was rebelling against the intrusion of this ancient, malevolent power."

"As they shuffled forward, their very presence seemed to draw the darkness closer, tendrils of shadow curling around their ankles like grasping fingers. The wind died, and an oppressive silence fell, punctuated only by the faint, maddening whisper of an unseen voice that seared the air with its malevolent intentions. The victims' gazes, once fixed on some distant point, began to shift, their eyes sliding towards the darkness, drawn by some morbid fascination, as if they sensed the presence of something terrible and ancient, waiting to reclaim its due."

"His eyes, once dull and uncomprehending, now gleamed with a sickly, otherworldly light, as if infected by the very essence of the darkness. The woman's hand, still gripping the child's, began to tremble, her fingers slowly relaxing as if released from some unseen weight, and her gaze, now vacant and unblinking, seemed to bore into the heart of the darkness, as if searching for some long-lost memory, or perhaps, some terrible truth."

"As the air seemed to grow colder, heavier with malevolent intent, the woman's free hand drifted up to her mouth, her fingers tracing the curve of her lips as if attempting to coax forth some long-silenced cry, and her eyes, those empty, dark wells, seemed to draw the shadows closer, as if absorbing the very darkness that surrounded them, until she was little more than a vessel, a hollow shell, eerily still and silent, her essence slowly being devoured by the void that yawned before her."

"The darkness began to seep into her pores, staining her skin with an otherworldly pallor, and her breath, once warm and gentle, grew cold and stale, as if she were exhaling the very life force that had driven her to this forsaken place, where the shadows writhe and twist like living things, taunting her with the promise of a final, eternal silence."

"The once-tender lines of her face now seemed chiseled from the same dark marble as the ancient ruins that surrounded her, their crumbling edges whispering secrets only the damned could hear, and her eyes, once bright as stars on a midnight sky, had sunk into hollows of despair, reflecting only the desolate landscape of her soul."

"As she stood there, frozen in time, a forgotten sentinel watching over the ruins of her own existence, the wind howled through the vacant streets like a chorus of the mournful, their sighs and wails merging with the cadence of her racing thoughts, echoes of memories long past, loves lost, and promises broken."

"The faint scent of smoke and rain lingered in the air, transporting her back to the day it all fell apart, the sound of shattering glass and splintering dreams still echoing in her mind as she stood there, a shadow of her former self, the weight of her sorrow threatening to consume her, as the city around her decayed, like her own once-vibrant soul, its beauty lost to the ravages of time, the wind its only constant companion, whispering secrets in her ear, reminding her of what she had, what she had lost, and what she would never regain."

"The whispers in her ear grew louder, taunting her with memories of the laughter, the tears, the whispered promises and the shattering consequences, and she felt herself being pulled backward, down the rabbit hole of nostalgia, as the city around her continued to crumble, its skyscrapers like crumbling tombstones, its streets like a once-thriving heartbeat now reduced to a mere echo, and she knew that if she let herself go, she would be forever lost in the fog of what could never be recaptured, trapped in a haze of what might have been."

"As she stood frozen, her mind reeling with the ghosts of her past, the city's eerie silence was shattered by the distant wail of sirens, and she felt the familiar tug of guilt and responsibility, as if the weight of her memories was somehow tied to the fate of the city itself, and she knew that if she didn't tear herself free from the grip of nostalgia, she would succumb to its toxic allure, and become just another relic of a forgotten era, lost among the detritus of a bygone age, her own heart reduced to a hollow echo, like the city around her."

"The sirens' mournful cries seemed to whisper her name, and she felt the cold wind of reckoning buffeting her, as if the city itself was calling her to account for her years of secrets and half-truths, and she knew that she could no longer delay the reckoning, for the ghosts of her past had grown loud and restless, demanding to be exorcised, and the weight of her memories was crushing her, threatening to consume her from the inside out."

"But she was not one to shy away from the shadows, for she had lived a life of secrets and deception, weaving a web of lies to ensnare the hearts of those who had foolishly trusted her, and now she felt the darkness closing in, like a noose tightening around her neck, as the ghosts of her past converged on her, their whispers growing to a deafening roar that drowned out the sound of her own heart beating."

"The memories that had long been buried, like the bodies of the dead she had once impersonated, began to claw their way out of the grave of her mind, their bones snapping as they rose up to haunt her, their faces twisted in a snarl of betrayal and rage, as she felt her grip on reality begin to slip, like sand pouring through the hourglass of her consciousness, leaving her lost and forsaken in the darkness that had been her companion all along."

"As she stumbled through the desolate landscape of her own mind, the whispers of the dead echoed through the chambers of her skull, their ragged breaths and mournful sighs a constant reminder of the lives she had lived, the identities she had stolen, and the secrets she had kept, each one a ghostly presence that shrouded her in an aura of perpetual dread and irredeemable guilt."

"The weight of their whispers grew louder with each step, a cacophony of sorrow and regret that threatened to consume her, as she traversed the twisted corridors of her own psyche, the shadows cast by their restless spirits dancing across the walls like macabre waltzers, orchestrating a deadly waltz of self-loathing and despair."

"As she stumbled through the darkness, the echoes of their judgments resonated within her, a maddening refrain that underscored every heartbeat, every pulse of her racing mind, the shadows deepening and darkening like a canvas of foreboding, until she felt herself becoming one with the abyss, a mere specter of her former self, forever trapped in this labyrinth of shattered dreams and fragmented identity."

"Her eyes, once bright and full of hope, now gleamed like embers from a long-dead fire, casting a faint, eerie glow on the desolate terrain that stretched out before her, the silence between the echoes growing heavier, thicker, a palpable shroud that suffocated her, and yet she moved on, driven by some morbid curiosity, some compulsion to confront the horrors that lurked within, to unravel the tangled threads of her shattered psyche and confront the monsters that lurked within her own reflection."

"The air grew colder, heavy with the stench of decay, as she delved deeper into the darkness, her footsteps echoing off the crumbling walls of a long-abandoned sanitarium, the rusting gates creaking in protest as she pushed them open, the wind whipping her hair into a frenzy as she stumbled into the heart of madness, where the walls ran crimson with the secrets of her own demise, and the echoes grew fainter, yet the silence remained, oppressive, crushing, a tombstone on her very soul."

"As she stepped further into the ruin, the darkness began to coalesce into shapes, whispers echoing through her mind of the countless souls who had met their maker within these walls, their pleas for mercy lost to the void, while the stench of decay clung to her like a shroud, and the sound of her own footsteps grew muffled, as if she was being pulled into a void of forgotten dreams, where the shadows themselves seemed to writhe and twist, as if alive, and the echoes of her own screams began to merge with the whispers of the dead, creating an eternal cacophony that threatened to consume her, body and soul."

"But still she pressed on, driven by a morbid fascination with the secrets the ruin held, her heart heavy with the weight of the terrible truths she uncovered, the whispers of the dead growing louder, urging her closer, as the shadows seemed to deepen, taking on a life of their own, reaching out like grasping fingers, attempting to snatch her back, into the darkness, where the echoes of screams would forever drown out the sound of her own thoughts, and she felt herself becoming one with the ruin, her sense of self dissolving, like salt in the void, leaving only the endless, nightmarish landscape of her own damnation, where the whispers of the dead would be her only companions, until the very end."

"Yet she could not resist the allure of the ruin's hidden chambers, the cryptic symbols etched into the walls seeming to pulse with a malevolent energy, drawing her deeper into the heart of darkness, where the air grew thick with the stench of decay and forgotten memory, and the whispers of the dead grew to a deafening roar, their voices a maddening cacophony of despair and longing, as if pleading with her to join them in their eternal slumber, to abandon the world of the living and surrender to the abyss of her own damnation."

"As she stumbled deeper into the depths of the ruin, the whispers grew louder, a chorus of the damned that seemed to reverberate through her very being, shaking the foundations of her sanity and dragging her inexorably towards the abyss, until she was standing at the threshold of a great, dank cathedral, its vaulted ceiling lost in darkness, and its walls lined with the silent, decaying statues of forgotten kings and queens, their eyes gleaming with a spectral light that seemed to burn with an otherworldly intelligence, as if watching her with cold, calculating purpose, and waiting for her to take her place among their ranks."

"The air was heavy with the scent of decay and rot, and the stone flags beneath her feet seemed to absorb the faint light that filtered through the grimy windows, leaving her to make out only the faintest outlines of the statues, their faces twisted in macabre grins, as if mocking her very presence. She could feel the weight of centuries of darkness bearing down upon her, and the whispers grew louder still, urging her forward, until she was compelled to step across the threshold, into the cold, dark heart of the cathedral, where the statues seemed to loom closer, their eyes burning with an unholy light, as if beckoning her to join them in their eternal silence."

"As she stepped further into the heart of the cathedral, the whispers grew to a deafening crescendo, the statues' macabre grins seeming to stretch wider in anticipation, their eyes blazing with an otherworldly intensity. She felt the air grow colder, the darkness thickening around her like a physical presence, and yet, she was drawn deeper, her feet moving of their own accord across the rough stone floor. The silence was oppressive, punctuated only by the soft scraping of her boots and the distant echoes of chanting, though she knew she was alone. Ahead of her, the high altar loomed, its elaborate stone carvings twisted and grotesque, seeming to writhe and twist in the flickering candlelight. And then, she saw it - the thing she had been searching for, the object of her deepest desire, waiting at the very heart of the cathedral."

"The artifact glowed with a faint, pulsing light, its surface etched with ancient symbols that seemed to shift and writhe like living serpents. She felt an overwhelming sense of longing, of yearning, as she reached out a trembling hand to touch its cool, smooth surface. And as she did, the whispers ceased, the silence deepening to a palpable silence that seemed to swallow her whole. The statues, the candlelight, the distant echoes of chanting - all faded away, leaving only her, the artifact, and the cathedral's dark, ancient heart. She was consumed by an unholy sense of power, of knowledge, and she knew that her life would never be the same again."

"As she gazed deeper into the artifact's glowing core, visions began to unfold before her eyes like scrolls unrolling from the very fabric of reality. She saw ancient civilizations rise and fall, saw wars fought and won, saw empires born and decayed. The visions seared themselves into her mind, leaving scorched trails of understanding and knowledge in their wake. The room began to fade away, replaced by a sweeping tapestry of time and space, with her own destiny stitched into its very fabric. And when the visions ceased, she knew that she was no longer the same person, for she had gazed upon the secrets of the universe and been forever changed."

"The silence that followed was oppressive, as if the very weight of the secrets she had unlocked threatened to crush her beneath its burden. She felt the world around her growing dim, the colors bleeding away to gray, like the fade of a sunset on a distant horizon. The artifact, still glowing softly in her hand, seemed to hum with an otherworldly energy, as if it were the source of the oppressive stillness. Suddenly, the air was filled with a thousand whispered names, each one a echo of a soul from a life long past, their stories and sorrows reverberating through her mind like the tolling of a great bell. She knew that she could not stay here, could not remain in this place of timeless knowledge and ancient pain."
